                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           Rs 2 crore for relief amp; rehab
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                              
	Bhubaneswar, Sept. 1: A day after his visit to violence-hit Khandhamal, chief minister Naveen Patnaik today reviewed the law and order situation in the district and released Rs 2 crore for relief, rehabilitation and restoration.        
	Naveen was informed by government officials that normality was limping back in the district.         
	He directed the officials to keep a close watch on the situation and take strong action for the protection of public life and property. Naveen also reviewed the ongoing relief and rehabilitation measures at camps set up in Khandhamal district.        
	While Rs 1 crore was released to the Khandhamal district administration for relief, another Rs 1 crore was provided to the Orissa State Disaster Mitigation Authority for undertaking rehabilitation measures, said chief secretary Ajit Kumar Tripathy.        
	It was decided that a high-level official team comprising home secretary T.K. Mishra, director-general of police G.C. Nanda, special relief commissioner N.K. Sundaray, rural development secretary S.N. Tripathy and health secretary T.K. Pandey would visit the district to supervise the law and order arrangements, relief work and health and sanitation measures.        
	Jeypore still tense        
	Tension continued to grip Jeypore even as curfew continued for the third day today.         
	The town witnessed clashes throughout the day as rioters ruled the roost at several places.         
	In an effort to disperse the mob, police had to lathicharge. There were incidents of stoning at police at several places with vehicles set on fire.         
	Two companies of paramilitary forces and 12 platoons of Orissa State Armed Police have been deployed in the area.                                                                                                                                                                         
